  "local_port": 40794,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My phone is not running 3G but 2G is working fine. 3G is working fine on another phone on the same sim. What can be the problem with my phone?",
  "response": "If your phone is not running 3G but 2G is working fine, and 3G works fine on another phone using the same SIM, the issue is likely related to your phone rather than the SIM or network. Here are some possible causes and troubleshooting steps:\n\n### **1. Incorrect Network Settings**\n   - Check if your phone's network mode is set to 2G only. To fix this:\n     - Go to **Settings** > **Network & Internet** > **Mobile Network** > **Preferred Network Type**.\n     - Select **3G** or **Auto (2G/3G/4G)** to enable 3G.\n   - If the option is missing, your phone may not support 3G (unlikely if it previously worked).\n\n### **2. Damaged or Faulty Antenna**\n   - The 3G antenna in your phone might be damaged or not functioning properly. This can happen due to physical damage, water exposure, or wear and tear.\n   - If this is the case, you\u2019ll need to take your phone to a repair center for inspection.\n\n### **3. Outdated Software**\n   - An outdated operating system or modem firmware might cause issues with 3G connectivity.\n   - Check for software updates in **Settings** > **System** > **Software Update** and install any available updates.\n\n### **4. SIM Slot Issue**\n   - The SIM slot in your phone might be faulty or not making proper contact for 3G signals.\n   - Try reinserting the SIM card or cleaning the SIM slot gently with a soft brush or cloth.\n\n### **5. Hardware or Modem Issue**\n   - There could be an issue with the phone's internal modem or hardware components responsible for 3G connectivity.\n   - If the phone is older or has been dropped, this is a possibility. A professional diagnosis and repair might be necessary.\n\n### **6. Carrier-Specific Settings**\n   - Some phones have carrier-specific settings or restrictions. Ensure that the APN (Access Point Name) settings are correct for your carrier.\n     - Go to **Settings** > **Network & Internet** > **Mobile Network** > **Access Point Names**.\n     - Verify the APN settings with your carrier's official configuration.\n\n### **7. Signal Interference or Weak Coverage**\n   - While this is less likely since 3G works on another phone, it\u2019s worth checking if your phone is in an area with weak 3G coverage or experiencing interference.\n   - Test the phone in a different location to rule this out.\n\n### **8. Phone Model Limitations**\n   - If your phone is an older model or a variant designed for a specific region, it might not support the 3G frequency band used in your area.\n   - Check your phone\u2019s specifications to confirm it supports the required 3G bands for your carrier.\n\nIf none of these steps resolve the issue, consult a professional technician or your phone\u2019s customer support for further assistance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
